I met with EJ Fanning this morning and myself and Stefanie Huffer (my assistant) surveyed the EWP project site at the Weinkle property at SR 786.  We surveyed both left and right ascending channels at the dredging locations upstream of the concrete fords, approximately 50 meters upstream of the these locations (ended just downstream of swinging bridge), and downstream about 110 m or to where the 2 channels rejoined.  In all, we sampled about 350 m given the separate channels at and below the project location.  The substrata was primarily cobble and a mix of pebble, with a few areas of sand/gravel/pebble/cobble; overall the substrata was relatively consolidated.  The flow at and downstream of the project was predominantly riffle/rapids, while upstream was a slow run.  Depths were about 0.3 m in the riffles/rapids and ranged from 0.5 to over 1.5 m in the upstream section.  The width ranged from about 7 m to 22 m, with the left ascending channel varying from 10-15 m and the right ascending channel varying from 7-12 m.  Flow in the left ascending channel was predominantly riffle/rapids and the right ascending channel varied from slow run to riffles.  Two culverted bridges are at the site.

COLLECTORS: M. McGregor, R. Steinberg, J. Baisden

Some fragmentary Unionidae relicts were found but unidentifiable as to speices or genus (possibly E. complanata and P. cataracta).  Crayfish and frogs were common.
